    "body": "<span class=\"solution-visible-txt\">All submissions for this problem are available.</span><p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Sherlock is defusing a bomb planted by Moriarty in the London subway. The bomb has <strong>N</strong> wires and <strong>N</strong> slots numbered <strong>1 to N</strong>. The slots are arranged continuously, left to right from <strong>1 to <strong>N</strong></strong>. Originally, wire number i should be plugged in slot number i, where <strong>1 &lt;= i &lt;= N</strong>. But, to confuse Sherlock, Moriarty plugged the wires into random slots, while maintaining that in one slot, there is atmost one wire. </p>\n<p> Sherlock believes that unplugging a contiguous sequence of wires would defuse the bomb. He can unplug a series of wires (a subarray), if it satisfies the following condition : There exists a wire numbered <strong>K</strong> such that <strong>K</strong>&lt;=(the minimum wire number in the subarray)+<strong>X</strong> and K>=(maximum wire number in the subarray)-<strong>Y</strong>. </p>\n<p> Sherlock wishes to unplug maximum number of wires he can. Watson, can you help him find the maximum length of the contiguous sequence of wires he can unplug?</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<h3>Input</h3>\n<p>The first line consists of three numbers <strong>N</strong>,<strong>X</strong>,<strong>Y</strong>. <br />The following line has N numbers representing the order in which the wires have been plugged in.  <br /><strong>i-th</strong> number represents the wire number that is plugged in the <strong>i-th</strong> position.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<h3>Output</h3>\n<p>The size of the longest subarray of wires Sherlock can unplug(continuous).</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<h3>Constraints</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>1</strong> \u2264 <strong>N</strong> \u2264 <strong>10^6</strong></li>\n<li><strong>1</strong> \u2264 <strong>X,Y</strong> \u2264 <strong>N</strong></li>\n</ul>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<h3>Example</h3>\n<pre><strong>Input:</strong>\n11 6 2\n7 3 2 6 11 1 10 4 8 9 5\n\n<strong>Output:</strong>\n5\n\n</pre><p>\u00a0</p>\n<h3>Explanation</h3>\n<p>The sub-array {10, 4, 8, 9, 5} is the longest sub array that satisfies the given constraints.</p>\n",
